to swing at me like that.

00:16:19.668 --> 00:16:20.501
- [Student] Get off!

00:16:20.501 --> 00:16:21.550
- A Kentucky deputy sheriff
- You don't get to

00:16:21.550 --> 00:16:24.309
swing at me like that.
- I still wanna say stop

00:16:24.309 --> 00:16:25.320
- Is handcuffing,
- You can do what we've

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:27.623
asked you to,
- an eight year old boy.

00:16:27.623 --> 00:16:29.082
- [Deputy] Or you can
suffer the consequences.

00:16:29.082 --> 00:16:30.137
- [Student] Ow no that hurts, stop!

00:16:30.137 --> 00:16:31.171
- [Deputy] Now sit down in that chair

00:16:31.171 --> 00:16:32.004
like I've asked you to.

00:16:32.902 --> 00:16:34.735
- [Student] I'm sorry!

00:16:35.617 --> 00:16:38.367
(student crying)

00:17:15.100 --> 00:17:18.290
- I promise you that I still have not,

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:21.290
I've watched this probably 25 times,

00:17:21.290 --> 00:17:24.950
the actual video goes on for 15 minutes

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:29.750
and you would think that
with a video like that

00:17:29.750 --> 00:17:31.730
you would take it to the sheriff

00:17:31.730 --> 00:17:35.100
and say you've got a rogue
sheriff deputy out here

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:39.030
and you gotta pull him in
and get him some training.

00:17:39.030 --> 00:17:42.293
We, our colleagues, our
co-council did that,

00:17:43.549 --> 00:17:45.903
the sheriff said absolutely not.

00:17:46.870 --> 00:17:50.053
This deputy did exactly
what he was supposed to do,

00:17:51.730 --> 00:17:54.840
we found out through discovery
that he had handcuffed

00:17:54.840 --> 00:17:58.970
some, between 10 and 15
children in the year that

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:00.493
he'd been doing this work.

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:04.610
That they asserted in their papers,

00:18:04.610 --> 00:18:08.340
because of course we sued that these eight

00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:11.888
and nine year old kids committing felonies

00:18:11.888 --> 00:18:13.526
(audience laughter)

00:18:13.526 --> 00:18:18.030
and have doubled down,
this is litigation that's

00:18:18.030 --> 00:18:20.670
been going on for two and a half years.

00:18:20.670 --> 00:18:24.520
We have gotten a good
judgment from the court

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:29.520
in the sixth circuit
that this was an unlawful

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:33.580
restraint it was excessive force by law

00:18:33.580 --> 00:18:35.850
we didn't have to go to court on that.

00:18:35.850 --> 00:18:39.580
But they won't settle they
are planning to appeal this

00:18:39.580 --> 00:18:40.630
to the supreme court.

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:44.507
So we--

00:18:45.990 --> 00:18:46.823
it's pretty bad,

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:54.390
they're furious that we have this video,

00:18:54.390 --> 00:18:59.390
it's and the video was
taken by school staff

00:19:00.100 --> 00:19:03.842
to show the mother how
difficult the child was being.

00:19:03.842 --> 00:19:05.821
(audience laughter)

00:19:05.821 --> 00:19:08.738
(audience chatter)

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:20.980
So handcuffing happens around the country,

00:19:20.980 --> 00:19:23.790
again another one of
these things that now that

00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:28.790
we're collecting we know happens
tens of thousands of times

00:19:29.130 --> 00:19:31.940
primarily against kids with disabilities,

00:19:31.940 --> 00:19:34.193
especially kids of
color with disabilities.

00:19:35.970 --> 00:19:39.320
This trial in Kentucky
we hope will eventually

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:42.120
send a bit of a message we're also working

00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:46.160
in Michigan with communities
in Flint to say look

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:48.610
we just don't want police
in elementary schools.

00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:50.653
We can have the argument
about how they are

00:19:50.653 --> 00:19:54.150
or are not in high schools
but in elementary schools

00:19:54.150 --> 00:19:55.750
there's no place for them

00:19:55.750 --> 00:19:59.340
and we would like your support there.

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:03.260
And we're also for those
schools where the communities

00:20:03.260 --> 00:20:06.410
are divided where some parents feel that

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:09.620
high schools are dangerous
and they want police there.

00:20:09.620 --> 00:20:13.260
We're trying to develop
model agreements so that

00:20:13.260 --> 00:20:16.530
police are clear that they're
not there to discipline

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:19.590
children that they're only there,

00:20:19.590 --> 00:20:23.173
if there's a danger or crime
that they need to intervene on.

00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:28.470
Okay 11 minutes left, conservatorships

00:20:28.470 --> 00:20:29.820
and supported decision making.

00:20:29.820 --> 00:20:32.110
What I usually come and
talk with you about,

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:37.110
so first of all conservatorships
are as most of you know

00:20:37.170 --> 00:20:40.110
they are called guardianships
in other parts of the country

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:45.050
are a huge deprivation of an
individual's civil liberties.

00:20:45.050 --> 00:20:47.690
It essentially takes legal personhood

00:20:47.690 --> 00:20:51.610
away from the individual,
if we're gonna take

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:55.380
that extreme a step a
step that some have called

00:20:55.380 --> 00:20:58.540
the most significant
deprivation of civil liberties

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:00.830
aside from the death penalty,

00:21:00.830 --> 00:21:02.810
we think you should
have a right to counsel.

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:06.090
So in Utah we are trying out this argument

00:21:06.090 --> 00:21:08.670
we don't know if we will
win yet, we'll learn a lot

00:21:08.670 --> 00:21:11.433
from the experience and we'll keep trying.

00:21:12.500 --> 00:21:16.220
Because we think that anyone
who is being threatened

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:18.560
with conservatorship or guardianship

00:21:18.560 --> 00:21:21.980
should have a counsel to
represent their stated interests.

00:21:21.980 --> 00:21:24.360
Not what their best interests
are which is what happens

00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:27.340
in many states, and in many circumstances,

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:30.440
that's already have someone
else substitute their

00:21:30.440 --> 00:21:34.080
decision making for
the individual but have

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:36.777
a counsel represent
their stated interests.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:40.350
We're also promoting
supported decision-making,

00:21:40.350 --> 00:21:42.340
which all of you I think have heard about

00:21:42.340 --> 00:21:45.410
a few times now, now that you've got this

00:21:45.410 --> 00:21:47.930
under your wing and thank
you we're starting to

00:21:47.930 --> 00:21:51.300
work more with our own
kind in the legal system.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:54.220
Judges so we're working
with the judicial council

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:56.710
to try and help judges
understand what supported

00:21:56.710 --> 00:22:01.220
decision-making is to
try and encourage them

00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:05.710
to urge that people try
supported decision-making

00:22:05.710 --> 00:22:08.560
before imposing a conservatorship.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:10.570
As the law actually requires,

00:22:10.570 --> 00:22:14.330
because in California
you have to use the least

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:15.903
restrictive measure possible.

00:22:17.670 --> 00:22:19.740
And we're developing more resources,

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:23.230
the MIND Institute has just
finished a series of videos

00:22:24.190 --> 00:22:27.580
and they are available on our website

00:22:27.580 --> 00:22:29.423
and the MIND Institute's website.

00:22:30.420 --> 00:22:35.420
Okay finally voting, it
seems important to end here

00:22:35.630 --> 00:22:37.763
it being the foundation of our democracy.

00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:43.680
But 41 states have laws
that disenfranchise people

00:22:44.670 --> 00:22:47.430
because of their disability status

00:22:47.430 --> 00:22:50.420
and four states have laws
that disenfranchise people

00:22:50.420 --> 00:22:54.860
who are idiots, so that is just such a

00:22:57.480 --> 00:23:01.080
an opportunity for satire,
of who would qualify.

00:23:01.080 --> 00:23:03.240
(laughter)

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:05.490
To be disenfranchised
in those states but is,

00:23:07.420 --> 00:23:10.630
just to be clear it is usually enforced

00:23:10.630 --> 00:23:13.780
against people with
developmental disabilities.

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:17.650
So in California almost
everyone who is put under

00:23:17.650 --> 00:23:21.250
a conservatorship also automatically lost

00:23:21.250 --> 00:23:26.250
their right to vote, the
solution was to amend

00:23:26.667 --> 00:23:29.100
the California electoral code

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:31.960
and the standard that
the disability community

00:23:31.960 --> 00:23:35.750
has come up with which I think
is just a superb standard

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:40.750
is that anyone who
expresses a desire to vote

00:23:41.430 --> 00:23:45.570
with or without accommodations
should be able to vote.

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:48.050
So whether the expression
needs an accommodation

00:23:48.050 --> 00:23:50.620
or being able to vote
needs an accommodation,

00:23:50.620 --> 00:23:52.933
that's the criteria we need to use.

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:57.970
So the law has been updated
thanks to my colleague

00:23:57.970 --> 00:24:01.440
Claudia Center and we just
need to get the word out.

00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:04.480
Our affiliates have been
doing that but to the extent

00:24:04.480 --> 00:24:09.480
that you can, we would like your help.

00:24:09.650 --> 00:24:14.650
Also online voter
registration huge benefit

00:24:14.790 --> 00:24:17.880
to the disability community,
you don't have to go down

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:20.870
fill out a form by hand,
make sure that they've got it

00:24:20.870 --> 00:24:23.760
right because the forms
that are filled out by hand

00:24:23.760 --> 00:24:25.830
are then translated and typed by people

00:24:25.830 --> 00:24:28.610
who can't necessarily read your writing.

00:24:28.610 --> 00:24:32.530
But for people who need
assistive technology,

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:36.730
to use websites almost all of the websites

00:24:36.730 --> 00:24:40.370
that were completed are inaccessible.

00:24:40.370 --> 00:24:45.070
So we did a report showing what
the most common errors were

00:24:45.070 --> 00:24:47.000
sent it to all the secretaries of states,

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:48.870
have been encouraging people to update

00:24:48.870 --> 00:24:51.660
their websites we're making progress

00:24:51.660 --> 00:24:54.303
and in New York we decided to sue,

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:59.770
the wrong state to sue and we
knew that they actually fight

00:24:59.770 --> 00:25:02.330
every lawsuit tooth and nail
but we didn't want to seem

00:25:02.330 --> 00:25:04.220
partisan and they're a democratic state.

00:25:04.220 --> 00:25:09.220
So that's where we sued, and
they have already improved

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:10.930
their website quite a bit

00:25:10.930 --> 00:25:13.553
and we are in settlement
negotiations there.

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:19.980
I would encourage you, I
know you are not one of the

00:25:19.980 --> 00:25:21.950
offices that is required by the

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:25.920
national voter registration
act to help your clients

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:28.280
come in to register to vote,

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:31.480
but if you can, if you have
the time ask them if they're

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:33.170
interested in voting, let
them know that they can

00:25:33.170 --> 00:25:38.170
register online and please
let us know if you hear

00:25:38.230 --> 00:25:39.740
of any problems.

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:41.940
We want to make sure that
this system is working

00:25:41.940 --> 00:25:44.840
even in California where we assume

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:47.430
and think most things
are going well California

00:25:47.430 --> 00:25:50.360
was the only state that the website

00:25:50.360 --> 00:25:51.810
was accessible to start with.

